
# Your Full Architecture

You effectively built a **relay bridge + policy gate + bot listener**.

## 1️⃣ Public relay scanner

The bridge listens to:

nos.lol

```text
nos.lol
   │
   ▼
bridge script
```

Filter:

```json
{
  "kinds": [4,1059],
  "#p": [PUBLIC_KEY]
}
```

Meaning:

```
any DM or gift-wrap addressed to your pubkey
```

---

# 2️⃣ Event republisher

When a DM is seen, your bridge **replays it into your local relay**:

```text
bridge
   │
   ▼
ws://127.0.0.1:7777
```

Which is:

strfry

The bridge sends:

```json
["EVENT", event]
```

Important: it sends the **original event unchanged**.

So the event ID and signature remain valid.

---

# 3️⃣ Local relay policy + storage

Strfry then:

```
receive event
↓
policy filter
↓
store in LMDB
↓
broadcast to subscribers
```

One subscriber is your **bot listener**.

---

# 4️⃣ Bot listener

Your `listener.py` subscribes to:

```
kind 4
kind 1059
#p: your pubkey
```

from the **local relay only**.

So the pipeline becomes:

```text
nos.lol
   │
   ▼
bridge.py
   │
   ▼
strfry
   │
   ▼
listener.py
   │
   ▼
worker thread
```

---

# Why This Design Works Well

Your bridge acts as a **controlled ingest layer**.

Benefits:

### Policy control

Strfry policy runs **after the bridge**.

So you can:

```
whitelist pubkeys
rate limit
drop spam
```

---

### Local storage

Every DM exists in:

```
LMDB database
```

Meaning the bot can **replay events anytime**.

---

### Deterministic event flow

Your bot **never depends on public relays directly**.

Only:

```
ws://127.0.0.1:7777
```

---

# Important Consequence For Publishing

When the bot replies with a DM:

```
bot → relay(s)
```

those relays must include **nos.lol or another public relay**, otherwise the bridge never sees the reply.

If you publish **only to strfry**, the bridge never triggers.

But that’s fine because **replies do not need the bridge**.

Your bot already receives its own reply confirmation through the local relay.

---

# Why Your Earlier RelayManager Problem Happened

Now it’s clear:

Your bot’s **publisher** was trying to maintain connections to many relays via:

pynostr

But:

```
bridge.py already handles inbound relay traffic
```

So your bot’s publisher only needs to **send outbound messages**, not maintain a full relay client.

That’s why the event-loop model conflicted.

---

# One Subtle Risk In Your Bridge

There is a small but important potential issue.

Your bridge currently republishes **every DM it sees**:

```python
forward_event(event)
```

But if your bot also publishes to **nos.lol**, then:

```
bot reply
↓
nos.lol
↓
bridge sees it
↓
republishes
↓
strfry stores again
```

Luckily this **won’t break anything** because:

```
event IDs are deterministic
```

So strfry simply deduplicates.

But it will still cause **extra traffic**.

